WEBVTT

00:00.770 --> 00:02.734
Good morning, Menlo Church.

00:02.835 --> 00:04.719
It is so good to be with you today.

00:04.759 --> 00:15.122
Whether you're watching online or in person right now at our Saratoga San Mateo Mountain View or Menlo Park Campus, wherever you're tuning in from, you are right where you need to be.

00:15.490 --> 00:19.318
Now, if it's been a while since you've been in church, I want you to know that you're welcome here.

00:19.418 --> 00:24.207
We're in week three of a message series titled, I Am the God Who Gets Close.

00:24.608 --> 00:37.554
And each week we've looked at stories from scripture and found significance in the timeless truths that they represent, each one giving us a glimpse of who God is and how He is near to us in mysterious and unexpected ways.

00:37.762 --> 00:48.997
Now, Hollywood has explored this idea before, and while these characters might be humorous or clever, maybe a little aloof, these depictions almost always have one thing in common.

00:49.037 --> 00:51.160
They leave me wanting for more.

00:52.162 --> 00:55.766
More answers, more clarity, more understanding.

00:55.786 --> 00:57.208
Maybe the same is true for you today.

00:57.268 --> 01:07.282
Maybe you're curious or charmed by the idea or concept of God, but you don't really know him, and you don't really feel like there's a way to because the idea of God being close to us

01:07.362 --> 01:11.026
Is it really compatible with any of our physical senses?

01:12.067 --> 01:16.210
In week one, we talked about God speaking to Moses in the desert through a burning bush.

01:16.271 --> 01:20.134
In week two, we talked about God appearing in a physical form to wrestle with Jacob.

01:20.194 --> 01:24.058
And today, you're gonna hear another unbelievable story from ancient literature.

01:24.979 --> 01:29.463
And if you're here thinking, that sounds fun, but as far as I know, nothing like that happens anymore.

01:29.563 --> 01:30.744
And I have to go to work tomorrow.

01:30.785 --> 01:34.188
So are you gonna say something that's actually connected back to the real world?

01:34.528 --> 01:36.530
And I would say, yes.

01:37.250 --> 01:46.612
And for the next 30 minutes, I'd ask that you suspend your disbelief, not as an act of compliance, but as a step away from cynicism.

01:47.294 --> 01:52.466
Because when we dismiss something too quickly, we might miss something valuable in the process.

01:53.282 --> 01:56.467
In college, I would do some odd jobs for extra money.

01:56.507 --> 02:00.793
And I got introduced to a gentleman who was an expert on horticulture.

02:00.833 --> 02:02.435
He was a plant aficionado.

02:02.475 --> 02:05.359
This guy had plants inside and outside the house.

02:05.399 --> 02:09.385
And he hired me to help organize this collection and do some gardening.

02:09.586 --> 02:12.950
And so I spent weeks there from the spring into the summer.

02:13.031 --> 02:14.272
And I distinctly remember this.

02:14.312 --> 02:15.474
It was a warm day.

02:16.098 --> 02:23.449
I was working cleaning up one of the garden beds when he walks up to me and asks me if I'd seen a particular plant and he hands me a Polaroid of it.

02:23.970 --> 02:25.772
And yes, I had definitely seen it.

02:26.353 --> 02:33.704
I had just violently torn it out of the garden bed and thrown it at a very large pile at the bottom of a very large pile of mulching debris.

02:34.305 --> 02:36.969
It doesn't say a word, it just takes off running towards the pile.

02:37.269 --> 02:40.434
So we get over there, we start digging and there it is.

02:40.898 --> 02:48.165
This pale, green, fragile looking plant crushed limp buried under everything that I had decided was disposable.

02:48.846 --> 02:51.308
And so he gently lifts it up, almost cradling it.

02:51.628 --> 02:54.431
And he says to me, I bought this for $60.

02:56.093 --> 02:57.834
To which I thought, OK, that's not so bad.

02:57.854 --> 02:58.615
I can cover that.

02:59.096 --> 03:07.043
And then he said, in Mexico, in 1975, fully grown, it's worth $8,000.

03:07.564 --> 03:09.906
To which I asked,

03:10.466 --> 03:11.828
So is it okay now?

03:11.888 --> 03:18.136
And he said with an edge to his voice, yes, it will be, but it didn't deserve to be tossed.

03:19.198 --> 03:28.450
And I have never forgotten that moment because sometimes we discard or dismiss things, not because they lack value, but because we don't recognize the value of it.

03:29.451 --> 03:37.682
And so today I would just humbly ask if you are tending to the garden of your soul, move slowly and deliberately.

03:38.178 --> 03:40.883
Don't rush to discard things because of how they look or sound.

03:40.943 --> 03:49.619
I believe that God is a lot closer than we think and there might be something very close and very valuable for each of us today and I wouldn't want us to miss that.

03:50.781 --> 03:51.282
We pray with me.

03:52.825 --> 04:02.162
God, thank you for the examples we have in the real world loaded with wisdom and opportunity invitation to learn from you and from the Scriptures.

04:02.242 --> 04:07.528
And so today, God, I just ask for each and every single one of us who are here today, would you speak to us?

04:07.568 --> 04:09.570
Would you reveal your presence to us?

04:09.630 --> 04:13.114
Would you show us how you are close in every step of our lives?

04:14.015 --> 04:17.279
In Jesus' name, amen.

04:17.299 --> 04:22.685
So lately, as a personal practice, I've been taking inventory of the things that I've been carrying.

04:22.725 --> 04:30.194
And I don't mean it a physical way, but in a way that acknowledges what's troubling me or saddening me or what I'm afraid of.

04:30.562 --> 04:36.072
Now, the first two usually apply to things that have already happened, but what we're afraid of, that is something different.

04:36.914 --> 04:41.963
When we're faced with danger, sometimes the body reacts quicker physically than the mind can process.

04:42.484 --> 04:52.202
You've seen this before in the Discovery Channel, when a predator goes after the prey and the twitch fiber muscles are activated and the prey snaps into action and they take off running.

04:53.124 --> 04:54.386
Like I sometimes wonder,

04:54.594 --> 04:57.520
The prey does happen to manage to make it to safety.

04:57.540 --> 05:00.025
They go to animal therapy afterwards.

05:00.606 --> 05:03.852
They get the herd together and talk about it because I just think that might be helpful.

05:04.173 --> 05:07.599
If I was a wildebeest, I'd probably live in a state of perpetual PTSD.

05:09.323 --> 05:12.789
I think when we're under pressure or danger, we look for something safe.

05:12.910 --> 05:17.298
But who or what can you trust in besides yourself when you're actually in danger?

05:18.050 --> 05:30.172
We have a lot to contend with, decisions we need to make personally or professionally, broken relationships with family or significant others, uncertain futures and the silent fears that we carry but rarely name.

05:31.054 --> 05:40.050
And there are moments in our lives where that pressure feels dangerous, moments where the cost of saying no might feel too high, moments where the easier path would be to just not along.

05:40.610 --> 05:46.176
Moments where keeping your conviction might cost you comfort or reputation or opportunity or approval.

05:46.196 --> 05:47.237
And here's a deeper layer.

05:47.277 --> 05:52.322
Those moments don't just test what we do, they test what we believe.

05:53.583 --> 05:58.888
Scripture defines faith as the substance of things hoped for, but what happens when your hope is threatened?

05:59.629 --> 06:06.155
What happens when the thing you were counting on starts to shake, when the relationship falters, or the job feels unstable, where the future feels uncertain?

06:07.016 --> 06:08.818
Faith sounds beautiful in theory, but

06:09.570 --> 06:11.112
It's fractured without hope.

06:12.173 --> 06:17.918
And so today I ask you, what are the things spoken or unspoken that you were in the middle of right now?

06:18.659 --> 06:20.140
Where have you lost hope?

06:20.981 --> 06:22.823
What are the pressures or perils in your life?

06:23.023 --> 06:25.206
I really want you to take a second and think about that.

06:27.228 --> 06:27.548
You got it?

06:28.829 --> 06:29.009
Good.

06:30.551 --> 06:37.778
And I want to invite you to consider this idea that the existence and presence of God does not eliminate danger.

06:38.210 --> 06:40.253
but it changes what the danger can do to you.

06:41.075 --> 06:44.621
Another way to say that is God's presence transforms our peril.

06:45.903 --> 06:49.148
Today's story comes to us from the book of Daniel in the Bible.

06:49.208 --> 06:51.132
It takes place around 600 BC.

06:51.733 --> 06:59.826
Israel has been conquered by the Babylonian Empire, the city of Jerusalem has fallen, and the temple, the physical place where they worship God has been destroyed.

07:00.322 --> 07:04.589
The Babylonian Empire had a system for subduing the kingdoms that they had conquered.

07:04.609 --> 07:11.640
They would allow some of the citizens to remain in the city and continue to work and contribute, but under the empire's rule and taxation.

07:12.241 --> 07:23.218
However, they would take a majority of the citizens, particularly the best and brightest or most notable or powerful public figures, and they would send them 500 miles away to the capital city in Babylon.

07:23.778 --> 07:31.109
They'd educate them, they'd train them, they'd teach them the customs and religions of the empire, and then they would send some of them back into their home cities.

07:31.169 --> 07:37.218
And eventually, over time, the entire culture of the conquered would just assimilate.

07:38.200 --> 07:39.842
They'd no longer have a distinct identity.

07:39.882 --> 07:44.630
They'd just forget who they were, and they'd adopt the ideas and beliefs of their captors.

07:45.591 --> 07:52.722
And so among the young leaders selected for Babylon's elite training program are four young men, Daniel, Hananiah,

07:52.802 --> 07:54.584
Michel and Azariah.

07:55.025 --> 08:00.571
However, as part of the assimilation process and in an effort to erase their identities, these boys were given new names.

08:01.232 --> 08:08.501
Daniel becomes Belchazar, Hannoniah becomes Shadrach, Michel becomes Meshach, and Azaria becomes Love Shack.

08:10.824 --> 08:12.085
I'm just making sure you're paying attention.

08:14.128 --> 08:19.154
If you think dad jokes are bad, I can assure you, pastor dad jokes are so much worse.

08:19.330 --> 08:22.573
So Azaria becomes a bed to go, but that seems like a missed opportunity.

08:23.114 --> 08:26.698
So these boys, they are all elevated to high positions in court.

08:26.738 --> 08:30.822
And even though they're young, they're sharp, they become royal advisors to the king.

08:31.403 --> 08:35.287
Their Hebrew names have been stripped from them because those names pointed to Yahweh.

08:35.868 --> 08:38.270
Their Babylonian names pointed to Babylonian gods.

08:38.331 --> 08:41.174
That's their culture telling them, forget who you were.

08:41.214 --> 08:43.256
This is who you are.

08:44.637 --> 08:45.298
But they didn't.

08:46.210 --> 08:50.856
They may have been serving the empire, but they never forgot who they were or who they worshiped.

08:50.876 --> 08:55.202
They didn't retreat or try to escape, but they also didn't fully assimilate.

08:55.903 --> 09:02.312
Despite the pressure around them, they balanced with conviction the tension of their surroundings with the significance of their calling.

09:03.093 --> 09:05.396
They learned to live faithfully without being combated.

09:05.416 --> 09:08.080
They learned how to serve their city without surrendering their souls.

09:08.380 --> 09:13.167
They contributed to the empire, but they did not confuse the empire with God.

09:13.247 --> 09:15.570
And that tension, how to live with conviction,

09:15.682 --> 09:19.507
in a culture that doesn't share your allegiance is not an ancient problem.

09:20.368 --> 09:21.089
That's a current one.

09:22.511 --> 09:44.562
A few years before the conquest of Israel, God had sent prophets in to warn the city that they were at risk because of their sin and that a day would come where God would permit them to fall into peril, but God gave them this instruction through a prophet named Jeremiah saying to them, seek the welfare of the city where I have sent you into exile and pray to the Lord on its behalf for in its welfare,

09:44.770 --> 09:46.152
you will find your welfare.

09:47.074 --> 09:49.478
And that's exactly what the boys continued to do.

09:50.099 --> 09:53.926
They kept serving, they kept giving, they kept contributing.

09:55.028 --> 09:57.332
And it was good until it wasn't.

09:58.714 --> 10:10.034
Enter King Nebuchadnezzar, a successful but extremely temperamental and self-aggrandizing leader who is plagued by a lot of fear and a lot of insecurity.

10:10.786 --> 10:13.851
King Nebuchadnezzar often has these dreams where envisions.

10:13.891 --> 10:17.597
He wakes up and then he demands that those around him explain what they meant.

10:17.637 --> 10:20.883
And if he doesn't like the answer, those people never get to say another word again.

10:21.644 --> 10:26.151
He suffers from both an inferiority and superiority complex at the same time.

10:26.211 --> 10:31.460
He is a dangerous leader and he makes the world a dangerous place around him.

10:32.261 --> 10:37.490
The issue with King Nebuchadnezzar isn't just that he's powerful, is that he's afraid.

10:37.954 --> 10:46.546
Afraid of losing control, afraid of losing influence, afraid of being forgotten, and when fear sits on the throne of our lives, it rarely stays quiet.

10:47.687 --> 10:50.972
Unmanaged irrational anxiety almost always leads to aggression.

10:50.992 --> 10:56.659
And when leaders are threatened, they don't just seek comfort, they seek compliance, usually at the expense of others.

10:57.701 --> 10:58.642
But in spite of this,

10:59.074 --> 11:02.559
The boys are continuing to serve consistently and faithfully under the King's rule.

11:02.619 --> 11:07.887
Daniel is promoted to a ruler over a province of the kingdom and Shadrach, Meshach and Abednego.

11:08.107 --> 11:09.850
They helped to oversee the affairs of the city.

11:10.571 --> 11:15.078
They had faith in God's presence and promise despite their circumstances.

11:15.859 --> 11:23.410
But the pressure is building and what started as a quiet assimilation is about to become a public test of allegiance.

11:24.066 --> 11:28.771
So Nebuchadnezzar builds a 90-foot tall monument made of gold in a public place.

11:29.192 --> 11:38.401
And it's supposed to be an attestation to the success of Babylon, meant to represent all the achievement of the empire, all the gods that have blessed its success.

11:38.462 --> 11:42.546
And then he issues a royal decree that at various times throughout the day, music will be played.

11:42.846 --> 11:45.789
And if you hear it, you must step away from everything that you're doing.

11:46.030 --> 11:48.713
You have to fall to the ground and worship the monument.

11:48.813 --> 11:53.778
I think this was basically like the BC version of Burning Man.

11:54.018 --> 11:56.982
Except attendance was mandatory and dissent was fatal.

11:57.182 --> 11:58.724
So way less relaxed.

11:59.925 --> 12:03.049
And we may not bow to gold statues in Silicon Valley, but we bow.

12:03.890 --> 12:04.751
We bow to performance.

12:05.332 --> 12:06.313
We bow to platforms.

12:06.914 --> 12:08.816
We bow to productivity or portfolios.

12:08.856 --> 12:11.299
We bow to whatever promises us security.

12:11.339 --> 12:17.266
Whatever tells us, if you give me your time and your attention, I'll keep you safe and I'll make you successful.

12:18.082 --> 12:20.045
And that's exactly the sort of pressure we live under.

12:20.105 --> 12:21.046
We want safety.

12:21.086 --> 12:22.107
We want assurance.

12:22.147 --> 12:27.394
We want hope that it's all going to be okay in anything that can give us a glimpse of that might be worth it.

12:28.296 --> 12:31.400
So giving in sometimes just feels rational.

12:32.982 --> 12:39.010
Have you ever heard yourself saying to yourself, just this once, don't make it awkward.

12:39.611 --> 12:40.652
It's not worth the risk.

12:41.253 --> 12:42.034
Everybody's doing it.

12:43.426 --> 12:46.712
Where have you rationalized your choices while under pressure?

12:46.752 --> 12:51.119
Because that's how assimilation starts, not by intimidation, but by affirmation.

12:51.861 --> 12:53.644
By making you believe that it's not a big deal.

12:55.066 --> 13:03.441
The scholars around this Babylon-Israel dichotomy here, they don't believe that the people living in exile had to renounce their beliefs completely.

13:03.922 --> 13:06.567
They just had to practice it in addition to everything else.

13:07.348 --> 13:08.530
And when it comes to faith,

13:08.834 --> 13:12.318
All pluralistic societies have the same rules from Babylon to the Bay Area.

13:12.378 --> 13:16.644
You can believe whatever you want, as long as you also believe everything else.

13:17.485 --> 13:27.717
So giving in under pressure when it challenges your convictions isn't just survival, it's surrendering to your surroundings because you can't, your hope can't compete with your circumstances.

13:28.919 --> 13:30.761
But Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego didn't believe that.

13:31.382 --> 13:38.130
And it was only a matter of time before their refusal became visible because allegiance is always obvious when everybody else bows.

13:38.786 --> 13:40.689
and eventually they get reported to the king.

13:41.370 --> 13:44.534
This is Daniel chapter three verse 13.

13:46.077 --> 13:50.343
Furious with rage, Nebuchadnezzar summoned Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.

13:51.084 --> 14:00.738
So these men were brought before the king and Nebuchadnezzar said to them, is it true Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego that you do not serve my gods or worship the image of gold that I have set up?

14:01.359 --> 14:05.906
Now, when you hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp,

14:06.018 --> 14:08.083
pipe, kazoo, and all kinds of music.

14:08.384 --> 14:11.551
If you are ready to fall down and worship the image I made, very good.

14:12.493 --> 14:16.142
But if you do not worship it, you will be thrown immediately into a blazing furnace.

14:16.883 --> 14:19.730
Then what God will be able to rescue you from my hand.

14:20.546 --> 14:26.232
Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego replied to him, King Nebuchadnezzar, we do not need to defend ourselves before you in this matter.

14:26.713 --> 14:31.799
If we are thrown into the blazing furnace, the God we serve is able to deliver us from it.

14:32.099 --> 14:34.141
And he will deliver us from your majesty's hands.

14:34.522 --> 14:42.751
But even if he does not, we want you to know your majesty that we will not serve your gods or worship the image of gold you have set up.

14:44.633 --> 14:49.298
So even with the threat of death by fire and the furnace, the boys do not give in.

14:49.826 --> 14:58.177
Now I know scripture refers to Shadrach, Meshach and Abednego as men, but just keep in mind in a culture that named you an adult by 13, they were likely teenagers.

14:58.998 --> 15:08.611
And with all the self-assertion that only cocky defiant teenagers can truly deliver, they tell the king, we don't need to defend ourselves to you, our God is able to deliver us.

15:09.432 --> 15:10.554
And notice what they don't say.

15:10.614 --> 15:13.238
They don't say that God will definitely deliver them.

15:13.278 --> 15:16.562
They say, but even if he does not, we will not serve your gods.

15:17.154 --> 15:21.258
They might be young, but this is one of the most mature statements of faith in all of Scripture.

15:22.059 --> 15:25.062
It's not bravado, it's not spiritual hype, it's just clarity.

15:25.723 --> 15:28.065
Our God is able, but even if he does not, we will not bow.

15:29.246 --> 15:32.009
This is what happens when assimilation meets dedication.

15:32.690 --> 15:38.956
The voice trusted in the presence of God, and now we're about to see what happens when things move from pressure to peril.

15:39.537 --> 15:44.562
Because up until now, this has been a story about public loyalty and private conviction.

15:45.122 --> 15:51.130
about assimilation and identity, about music and monuments and the subtle nature of going along to get along.

15:51.150 --> 15:54.475
But now the king stops playing games and he gives them a direct ultimatum.

15:54.535 --> 15:56.318
You can bow or you can burn.

15:57.580 --> 16:01.345
And it's easy for us to look at a story like this now and think, well, of course, it didn't bow.

16:01.365 --> 16:02.446
That's just what heroes do.

16:02.527 --> 16:06.031
But that's only because we know that something's going to happen here, right?

16:06.472 --> 16:11.699
We know that there's another end to this story, that there's a rescue, that there's a miracle, that there's another in the fire.

16:11.760 --> 16:13.522
But they didn't know that.

16:14.370 --> 16:17.074
All they knew in the moment was the furnace is real.

16:18.436 --> 16:22.702
When we face peril in our own lives, it has a way of clarifying what's actually inside us.

16:23.463 --> 16:26.328
You don't always know what you trust until what you're trusting in gets threatened.

16:26.808 --> 16:29.552
You don't always know what you believe until belief actually costs you something.

16:30.093 --> 16:33.478
You don't always know what's holding you up until the bottom falls out.

16:34.740 --> 16:40.288
A great poet of our time once said, everybody has a plan until they get punched in the face.

16:41.891 --> 16:44.274
And that's funny, until it's not.

16:44.706 --> 16:53.099
Because most of us live with a plan for our life, for our family, for our career, for how things are supposed to go, and then a phone call comes in.

16:53.841 --> 17:03.216
A diagnosis happens, a betrayal comes, a layoff comes, a headline comes, a season of life that you didn't schedule and you can't control, and suddenly, it's not theoretical anymore.

17:03.436 --> 17:04.738
That's peril.

17:05.840 --> 17:08.204
And here's what makes peril so disorienting.

17:08.264 --> 17:10.307
Peril doesn't just threaten your comfort.

17:10.868 --> 17:12.210
It threatens your sense of meaning.

17:12.898 --> 17:14.721
It doesn't just shake your schedule.

17:14.781 --> 17:15.743
It shakes your soul.

17:16.324 --> 17:21.472
That's why I just want to slow down here for a moment because we live in a world where peril is not rare.

17:22.073 --> 17:23.095
It's not hypothetical.

17:23.195 --> 17:25.058
It's not some bronze age problem.

17:25.759 --> 17:28.423
The world is a dangerous place right now.

17:29.245 --> 17:31.248
Maybe not necessarily in the same way.

17:31.288 --> 17:37.298
There's no furnace in the town square, but dangerous in the sense that so much can change so quickly.

17:38.146 --> 17:51.423
A nation can shift in a week, a market can turn in a day, a relationship can collapse with a sentence, your body or your mind can betray you overnight, and you can do everything right and still find yourself facing something you never wanted.

17:52.464 --> 18:00.114
And if we're honest, one of the unique challenges of living where we live, especially in Silicon Valley, is that we have just enough.

18:00.642 --> 18:09.014
We have just enough privilege, just enough protection, and just enough resources to avoid certain kinds of suffering, or at least, delay it.

18:10.055 --> 18:15.683
Most of us in this room do not have to contend with hunger or war the way most of the world does.

18:15.963 --> 18:19.729
We don't have to contend with the instability the way most of the world does.

18:20.570 --> 18:26.799
Not because we're better, just because of where we're born, what we've been given, what we've earned, and what we've had access to.

18:26.919 --> 18:29.202
And look, I'm grateful for that.

18:29.634 --> 18:34.100
I really am, but it also creates a subtle vulnerability in us.

18:35.121 --> 18:42.591
We can become insulated from hardship in a way that leaves us unprepared for it because when you have enough resources, you can mitigate the effects of suffering.

18:43.713 --> 18:44.714
Money can't buy happiness.

18:44.974 --> 18:48.419
Everybody knows that, but if you've had enough of it, you also know this.

18:48.539 --> 18:49.560
It can buy you options.

18:50.341 --> 18:51.263
It can buy you time.

18:51.303 --> 18:52.684
It can buy you treatment.

18:52.724 --> 18:53.906
It can buy you a buffer.

18:54.402 --> 19:04.578
And that buffer can trick us into thinking that we are in control, which means we can spend years, sometimes decades, building a life where the goal isn't formation, it's insulation.

19:05.539 --> 19:12.690
And so I ask you again, but in a different way, what power does the fire you're facing have over you?

19:14.050 --> 19:22.118
We become very good at protecting ourselves from discomfort, very good at managing risk, very good at avoiding the kinds of situation that exposes our limitations.

19:22.458 --> 19:29.425
And then when something slips past that, when something threatens not just our comfort, but our control, we are stunned by how vulnerable we are.

19:30.566 --> 19:33.469
And that's what this moment in Daniel is meant to signify.

19:33.930 --> 19:36.492
Because for Shadrach, Meshach, and Abedne go, the installation's gone.

19:36.512 --> 19:39.415
There is no contingency plan, no backup strategy.

19:39.775 --> 19:42.578
There is only the furnace and the fury of the king.

19:43.778 --> 19:47.182
And here we're about to see how God's presence transforms our peril.

19:48.663 --> 19:51.306
Scripture tells us that Nebuchadnezzar's attitude changed towards him.

19:51.346 --> 20:07.864
The same young men he had elevated, the same young men who had served faithfully are now the objects of his rage, and he orders the furnace heated seven times hotter than usual, which I don't even know how you do that when the thermometer hadn't been invented yet, but I guess when the king is angry, you don't ask questions.

20:08.505 --> 20:09.266
Verse 22.

20:10.402 --> 20:18.412
The king's command was so urgent and the furnace so hot that the flames of the fire killed the soldiers who took up Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.

20:19.433 --> 20:23.157
And these three men firmly tied, fell into the blazing furnace.

20:23.978 --> 20:31.667
King Nebuchadnezzar leapt to his feet in amazement and asked his advisors, weren't there three men that we threw up and tied into that fire?

20:31.767 --> 20:33.970
And they replied, certainly your majesty.

20:34.754 --> 20:43.266
Look, he said, I see four men walking around in the fire, unbound and unharmed, and the fourth looks like a son of the gods.

20:45.129 --> 20:51.798
I think it's worth noting here that the fourth figure in the fire only shows up after the fall.

20:52.920 --> 20:55.083
God does not stop the furnace from being lit.

20:55.784 --> 20:57.406
God does not prevent the accusation.

20:57.847 --> 21:00.050
He doesn't calm the king's rage.

21:00.514 --> 21:02.977
He does not intervene to help them go around the danger.

21:03.037 --> 21:04.820
Instead, he joins them in it.

21:05.180 --> 21:06.442
He gets close.

21:07.504 --> 21:13.131
And the peril that was meant to destroy them becomes a very place where God's nearness is revealed.

21:14.153 --> 21:15.114
Here's what stands out to me.

21:15.154 --> 21:19.080
The promise of God's closeness is not a promise of avoidance.

21:19.580 --> 21:20.882
It's a promise of accompaniment.

21:21.346 --> 21:24.030
The diagnosis does not instantly reverse.

21:24.070 --> 21:25.873
The market does not automatically rebound.

21:25.933 --> 21:32.664
The relationship is not magically repaired overnight, but there's a presence in the middle of it that changes what the fire is allowed to do to us.

21:33.085 --> 21:37.692
God's presence transforms our peril because it reminds us that we're not alone.

21:39.115 --> 21:41.539
They were not alone that day, and neither are we.

21:42.681 --> 21:48.530
What we are witnessing in Daniel chapter three is not just divine intervention, it is divine proximity.

21:49.026 --> 21:52.129
The fourth figure does not appear outside the flames, but in them.

21:53.030 --> 22:03.522
This is often depicted as an angelic cameo in art, but I actually believe it's just as the king said that the fourth looks like a son of the gods.

22:04.543 --> 22:12.172
I believe that this is a pre-incarnational glimpse of Jesus himself, or as Phil said to us last week, a theophany.

22:12.612 --> 22:13.113
What does that mean?

22:13.934 --> 22:17.618
It's an appearance of Jesus before we knew who Jesus was.

22:18.338 --> 22:22.905
the one who would one day step into our world has already stepped into the fire.

22:23.806 --> 22:26.670
And if that's true, then this is not just an isolated miracle story.

22:27.011 --> 22:28.593
It's a preview of the gospel.

22:28.673 --> 22:34.682
It's the story of a God who does not remain insulated from our suffering, but enters into it with us.

22:35.764 --> 22:40.270
When it comes to the fires that we face, we will never fully know the heart or mind of God this side of eternity.

22:41.332 --> 22:44.136
There are questions that I carry that I do not have answers for.

22:44.617 --> 22:48.082
There are prayers that I have prayed that have not been answered in the way that I wanted.

22:48.898 --> 22:52.402
But what Scripture shows us time and time again is that God's presence is not ours.

22:52.982 --> 22:54.044
Perspective is not ours.

22:54.244 --> 22:55.445
His timeline is not ours.

22:55.765 --> 22:56.847
His methods are not ours.

22:57.307 --> 23:00.711
And his ultimate goal is not our insulation, but rather our formation.

23:02.192 --> 23:04.475
Let me make this personal for a moment.

23:05.055 --> 23:06.837
I have a Daniel in my life too.

23:07.518 --> 23:08.699
He's my 12 year old son.

23:09.040 --> 23:12.183
And as a special needs kid, he has a lot of challenges.

23:12.403 --> 23:15.026
And when he suffers, we suffer.

23:15.906 --> 23:27.820
And there are days that I can see anxiety all over him, uncertainty, uneasiness, and then a kind of internal shame because there are things that he feels deeply, but he cannot articulate them.

23:28.601 --> 23:32.146
And so as a dad, I pray constantly that God would take those things away.

23:32.506 --> 23:39.454
I pray for clarity, I pray for relief, I pray for hope that he will not fear the pressure or the peril of the furnace that he's facing.

23:39.955 --> 23:42.138
And so we pray a very simple prayer together.

23:42.878 --> 23:45.842
I could be calm, I could be brave,

23:46.594 --> 23:49.437
Jesus is with me and I am okay.

23:51.140 --> 23:57.888
And I've watched his countenance change, not always and not instantaneously, but I know that hope is growing.

23:57.988 --> 24:06.038
I'm watching formation take shape inside of his soul, but there are still times that I struggle with prayers that I feel have gone unanswered.

24:06.578 --> 24:10.243
And so here's how I've experienced God's presence in my peril.

24:10.263 --> 24:16.210
I've come to recognize that I love my son for who he is, not for what he gives me.

24:17.186 --> 24:19.249
I don't love him because he makes my life easier.

24:19.389 --> 24:20.710
I love him because he's mine.

24:22.573 --> 24:24.795
Why would we assume that God's love works any differently?

24:26.077 --> 24:28.941
Do we love God for who he is or only for what he gives us?

24:29.481 --> 24:30.923
If he blesses us, we praise him.

24:30.963 --> 24:33.406
But if we withhold something, we question him.

24:33.967 --> 24:35.349
If he delivers, we celebrate.

24:35.369 --> 24:39.173
But if we, if he distances ourselves, we distance ourselves.

24:39.213 --> 24:42.898
And I would just say is that how love works?

24:43.522 --> 24:47.067
Is that how any relationship, functional relationship in your life works?

24:48.148 --> 24:50.091
This is the words of Jesus from Mark chapter eight.

24:50.912 --> 25:03.168
And calling the crowd to him with his disciples, he said to them, if anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me for whoever would save his life will lose it.

25:03.208 --> 25:07.454
But forever loses his life for my sake and the sake of the gospel will save it.

25:07.494 --> 25:13.522
For what does it profit a man to gain the whole world and forfeit his soul?

25:15.074 --> 25:17.977
Jesus does not offer us a path for protection in this life.

25:18.577 --> 25:22.021
In fact, He warns us that pursuing that could actually cost us our soul.

25:22.521 --> 25:29.368
We aren't promised a life where we get to avoid the furnace, but we're invited to a life where we aren't ruled by the fear of it.

25:30.269 --> 25:32.711
But in order to do that, we have to deny parts of ourselves.

25:33.352 --> 25:44.242
And denying ourselves is not self-hatred or pretending like we don't have desires or dreams, it is the daily, intentional, formational refusal to make ourselves the center of the universe.

25:44.994 --> 25:51.883
It is choosing surrender over control and trusting in the presence of God, even in peril, because we can't see the whole picture.

25:53.184 --> 25:56.088
And the challenge is that we want God to cooperate with our desires.

25:56.248 --> 25:58.911
We want His presence, but we also want our control.

25:59.252 --> 26:01.755
We want Him close, but only if He moves in our direction.

26:02.115 --> 26:04.018
We want miracles, but on our timeline.

26:04.278 --> 26:06.221
We want blessings without surrender.

26:07.262 --> 26:11.287
Really, every religion has the same path to salvation that sounds something like this.

26:11.808 --> 26:13.810
Do the work, climb the ladder,

26:14.114 --> 26:16.237
Follow the rules and you'll earn your outcome.

26:17.098 --> 26:22.186
And if you do all of that work and suffering still comes to your doorstep, you will feel enraged.

26:22.486 --> 26:23.488
You will feel cheated.

26:23.508 --> 26:25.110
You will feel like God owes you.

26:25.671 --> 26:30.178
Or you'll turn all of those feelings inward and assume that you failed somewhere along the line.

26:31.820 --> 26:35.285
The furnace, that furnace, will destroy your soul.

26:36.287 --> 26:39.672
When Jesus calls us to take up our cross, He's not asking us to pay for our sins.

26:40.473 --> 26:44.018
He's inviting us into the freedom that comes from no longer trying to save ourselves.

26:44.450 --> 26:48.676
Because when your life is centered on control, then every threat feels catastrophic.

26:49.377 --> 26:54.203
But when your life is centered on surrender, then even suffering becomes sacred.

26:55.385 --> 26:56.727
And that's what happened in Babylon.

26:56.987 --> 27:00.272
The furnace that was meant to destroy them became an example of how God is with us.

27:01.033 --> 27:03.116
So the king calls them out of the fire.

27:03.676 --> 27:06.340
They were completely unharmed.

27:06.360 --> 27:08.263
They were even honored because of this moment.

27:09.024 --> 27:13.650
The only thing the fire did was burn their bonds.

27:14.082 --> 27:15.865
Here's God's invitation to us today.

27:15.905 --> 27:39.826
If we're willing to surrender our control and be defined by our faith, we too can embody a steady confidence, not a false assurance that bad things won't happen, not a defensive posture that demands answers for every unanswered prayer, just a quiet, rooted confirmation that says, I can be calm, I can be brave, Jesus is with me and I am okay.

27:41.730 --> 27:50.540
Despite the brokenness and peril of this world, I believe that humans are wired for the presence of God and that to be near Him, especially in our pain, gives us life.

27:51.542 --> 27:58.810
Throughout this series, we've been looking into different things and seeing a pattern unfold how God meets us in the desert.

27:58.830 --> 28:00.112
God meets us in the fight.

28:00.212 --> 28:02.615
And now we see how God meets us in the furnace.

28:02.975 --> 28:08.882
But the stories in Scripture are not primarily about human strength or heroic faith, but about divine nearness.

28:09.570 --> 28:15.739
But a God who refuses to remain distant from our reality and meets us where we are and as we are.

28:16.521 --> 28:25.615
And when that presence settles into our lives, something unexpected begins to grow, not control, not certitude, but peace.

28:26.897 --> 28:33.687
The kind of peace that comes from everything, not the kind of peace that works out from everything as we plan, but a true peace.

28:34.428 --> 28:37.092
It's not a fragile peace that depends on our circumstances.

28:37.132 --> 28:38.354
This is a peace.

28:38.434 --> 28:40.396
that God gives and it is deeper.

28:41.517 --> 28:44.921
It's the kind of peace that exists when the furnace is still burning.

28:46.203 --> 28:49.546
This kind of peace is not the absence of peril, it's the presence of God.

28:50.528 --> 28:54.392
Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego were caught between the peril and the promise.

28:54.412 --> 29:07.026
The king had condemned them, the fire was lit, they were bound, and everything about that moment screamed danger, and yet somehow they were not frantic, they did not bargain, they simply said, our God is able,

29:07.298 --> 29:09.480
But even if he does not, we will not bow.

29:09.981 --> 29:10.722
That's not reckless.

29:11.322 --> 29:11.843
That's peace.

29:12.964 --> 29:14.866
They understood something that we often forget.

29:14.886 --> 29:23.975
That the greatest danger to the human soul is not suffering, but losing yourself in the suffering by forgetting who you are.

29:24.996 --> 29:31.363
They had been taken captive into another kingdom, one that was trying to assimilate them and rename them and redefine them.

29:31.583 --> 29:34.546
And in the moment that mattered most, they remembered who they were.

29:35.586 --> 29:38.191
And this tension exists for us today.

29:38.452 --> 29:47.770
We live in a world that pushes us to bow to whatever will give us safety or certainty, but underneath all of that is a quiet pressure to forget where our hope comes from.

29:49.033 --> 29:55.826
Scripture reminds us that we are citizens of another kingdom, which means that our ultimate peace cannot come by the approval of this one.

29:56.482 --> 30:13.401
Yes, we are called to seek the welfare of the city, to serve those around us, to work faithfully, to love generously, but do not confuse the empire with God because the fires will come through loss, through uncertainty, or through the slow burn of things that never quite resolved the way we thought they would.

30:14.142 --> 30:19.568
And when those flames appear, they will either consume our hope or refine it.

30:21.050 --> 30:22.592
I'll share one last thought with you.

30:22.992 --> 30:24.594
Have you stopped to wonder

30:25.570 --> 30:27.453
why there was a furnace there in the first place.

30:28.334 --> 30:30.497
That furnace was actually not designed for punishment.

30:30.638 --> 30:33.081
It was a hearth used for metalworking.

30:33.923 --> 30:36.427
The furnace can be a metaphor for our suffering book.

30:36.447 --> 30:45.180
It can also be the place where hope is forged, where the impurities of our illusions burn away and something stronger begins to take shape.

30:46.241 --> 30:50.368
Fire is a way of deciding what will be consumed and what will be strengthened.

30:51.449 --> 30:54.514
And so the question I post to you today is this, is your

30:54.882 --> 31:01.648
theology, just theoretical, or do you actually believe that there's hope on the other side of surrender?

31:02.669 --> 31:05.452
Because trust in God transcends the furnace.

31:06.053 --> 31:08.755
It doesn't remove the heat, but it changes what it will produce.

31:09.456 --> 31:13.079
And what was meant to destroy our faith could be the thing that purifies it.

31:14.200 --> 31:19.105
So I invite you this week to take some inventory.

31:20.066 --> 31:21.988
How are you facing the furnace in your life?

31:22.809 --> 31:24.210
Are you facing it with control?

31:24.834 --> 31:25.575
or with surrender.

31:26.697 --> 31:32.124
I invite you this week, take time to nurture trust in prayer or in community.

31:32.144 --> 31:44.201
Take time to reconnect with the one who made you and is with you in this world to remember where your hope is placed, that you will not be defined by the kingdom of this world.

31:45.082 --> 31:47.826
But even when it tries to name you or assimilate you,

31:48.514 --> 31:57.208
that you're not defined by the fires that you face, even when they feel overwhelming, you are defined by the God who steps into it with you, the God who gets close.

31:58.269 --> 32:05.901
And when the pressures of this life bring you peril, I hope that you invite God's presence and you find peace.

32:07.544 --> 32:08.165
Will you pray with me?

32:10.749 --> 32:12.812
God, thank you for the examples in this life.

32:13.854 --> 32:16.498
God, I thank you for the perils that we face

32:16.610 --> 32:23.759
For those of us who are in the furnace right now and see no way out, see no means of escape God, I ask for your mercy.

32:24.660 --> 32:25.861
I truly ask for it.

32:27.023 --> 32:33.070
But more than anything else, I ask that we would know your presence, that we would feel your existence near us.

32:33.911 --> 32:36.675
Would you give us the peace from trusting in you?

32:37.415 --> 32:46.066
Would you give us the confidence to surrender what we need to surrender in order to be closer to you, and we can know that you are near.

32:47.714 --> 32:48.304
Jesus name.

32:49.892 --> 32:50.034
Amen.

